(42, 7, 29, 40, 21, 31, 32, 'baptized with the baptism of John', 'Baptism and Belief in John', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in John the Baptist''s message. Both passages emphasize the response of publicans to John''s call, contrasting their acceptance with the rejection by others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 29, 44, 18, 25, 25, 'baptized with the baptism of John', 'Connection of Baptism of John', 'This connection highlights the significance of the baptism of John in both passages. In Luke, people are justified by being baptized with John''s baptism, while in Acts, Apollos is described as knowing only this baptism, indicating its importance in early Christian teaching.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 30, 42, 13, 34, 34, 'rejected the counsel of God', 'Rejection of God''s Counsel', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s messengers. In Luke 7:30, the Pharisees reject God''s counsel, while in Luke 13:34, Jerusalem is depicted as killing the prophets sent to them.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 30, 24, 8, 8, 8, 'rejected the counsel of God', 'Rejection of Divine Counsel', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s guidance. In Luke, the Pharisees reject God''s counsel, while in Jeremiah, the scribes claim wisdom despite their failure to uphold the law. This connection highlights a theme of false confidence in spiritual understanding.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 30, 40, 22, 35, 35, 'lawyers rejected the counsel of God', 'Connection Between Pharisees and Lawyers', 'Both passages emphasize the role of lawyers in challenging Jesus. The Pharisees and lawyers'' rejection of God''s counsel in Luke connects to the lawyer''s questioning of Jesus in Matthew.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 30, 47, 6, 1, 1, 'counsel of God', 'Rejection of God''s Counsel', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejecting God''s guidance. Both passages emphasize the importance of responding to God''s grace and counsel appropriately.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 30, 44, 20, 27, 27, 'counsel of God', 'Counsel of God Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of the ''counsel of God'' in both passages. Luke 7:30 discusses the rejection of God''s counsel, while Acts 20:27 emphasizes the declaration of that same counsel.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 30, 45, 10, 21, 21, 'rejected the counsel of God', 'Rejection of God''s Counsel', 'This connection highlights the theme of disobedience to God''s guidance. Both passages emphasize the rejection of divine counsel, with the Pharisees in Luke and Israel in Romans being described as disobedient.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 30, 48, 2, 21, 21, 'rejected the counsel of God', 'Rejection of God''s Counsel', 'This connection highlights the rejection of God''s counsel in both passages. The Pharisees'' rejection of baptism reflects a broader theme of rejecting divine grace, which is further emphasized in Galatians where righteousness through the law is dismissed.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 31, 40, 11, 16, 19, 'this generation', 'Comparison of Generational Attitudes', 'Both passages emphasize the attitudes of ''this generation'' and their responses to prophetic figures. They illustrate how the generation reacts differently to John the Baptist and Jesus, highlighting their refusal to engage with the messages presented to them.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 31, 25, 2, 13, 13, NULL, 'Comparison of Generations and Witnesses', 'This connection highlights the theme of likening and comparison in both passages. Luke 7:31 questions the nature of the current generation, while Lamentations 2:13 seeks to find a witness or comparison for Jerusalem, emphasizing the struggle to articulate their experiences.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 31, 41, 4, 30, 30, NULL, 'Comparison of Generations and Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the use of comparison in both passages. Both Jesus asks how to liken a group or concept, emphasizing the need for relatable illustrations.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 32, 40, 11, 16, 19, 'We have piped unto you, and ye have not danced', 'Children in the Marketplace', 'Both passages emphasize the metaphor of children in the marketplace, highlighting a generation''s indifference to the messages of John and Jesus. The repeated phrase about piping and mourning illustrates the failure to respond to calls for joy or lament.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 32, 20, 17, 16, 16, NULL, 'Wisdom and Response to Instruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of receptiveness to wisdom and instruction. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the failure to respond appropriately, whether to the call for joy or mourning in Luke or the pursuit of wisdom in Proverbs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 32, 24, 5, 3, 5, 'ye have not wept', 'Rejection of Correction Theme', 'Both passages emphasize a refusal to respond to calls for action or correction. In Luke, the children represent those who do not engage with the message, while Jeremiah describes people who refuse to grieve or return despite being stricken.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 32, 23, 28, 9, 13, 'we have piped unto you, and ye have not danced', 'Children and Rejection of Message', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages. In Luke, the children call out but are ignored, paralleling Isaiah''s depiction of people who do not heed the message despite its clarity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 32, 23, 29, 11, 12, NULL, 'Children and Response to Messages', 'This connection highlights the theme of unresponsiveness to calls for action. Both passages emphasize a lack of understanding or engagement with messages, whether joyful or mournful.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 32, 38, 8, 5, 5, 'children sitting in the marketplace', 'Children Playing and Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of children in both passages. Luke 7:32 mentions children calling to one another, while Zechariah 8:5 describes boys and girls playing, emphasizing the joy and communal interaction of youth.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 33, 42, 1, 15, 15, NULL, 'Connection of John the Baptist''s Lifestyle', 'Both passages emphasize John the Baptist''s abstention from wine. This connection highlights his unique role and dedication as a prophet filled with the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 33, 41, 1, 6, 6, 'eating bread nor drinking wine', 'John the Baptist''s Lifestyle', 'This connection highlights the contrasting depictions of John the Baptist''s lifestyle. Luke notes his abstention from food and drink, while Mark describes his diet of locusts and honey.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 33, 24, 16, 8, 10, 'eating bread nor drinking wine', 'Contrast of Eating and Drinking', 'This connection highlights the contrast between John the Baptist''s ascetic lifestyle and the feasting mentioned in Jeremiah. Both passages emphasize the rejection of societal norms related to eating and drinking, reflecting a deeper spiritual message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 33, 40, 3, 4, 4, 'eating bread nor drinking wine', 'John the Baptist''s Lifestyle', 'Both passages emphasize John the Baptist''s ascetic lifestyle. Luke notes his abstention from food and drink, while Matthew describes his diet of locusts and wild honey.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 33, 43, 8, 48, 48, 'He hath a devil', 'Accusations of Demonic Influence', 'Both passages emphasize accusations of having a devil. John the Baptist and Jesus are both labeled as possessed or influenced by evil, reflecting a common theme of rejection by their contemporaries.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 33, 43, 10, 20, 20, 'He hath a devil', 'Accusations of Madness', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation of having a devil. In Luke, John the Baptist is said to have a devil, while in John, others claim Jesus is mad and has a devil.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 33, 44, 2, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Mockery and Wine', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of mockery associated with wine. In Luke, John the Baptist is criticized for his abstinence, while in Acts, the apostles are mocked for appearing to be ''full of new wine.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 7, 34, 42, 15, 2, 2, 'a friend of publicans and sinners', 'Connection of Eating with Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' association with sinners through eating and drinking. The Pharisees'' criticism in both verses highlights their perception of Jesus as a friend of publicans and sinners.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
